Use two global variables:

* **prodMax**: max accumulative product of the array which ends on current position
* **prodMin**: min accumulative product of the array which ends on current position

For each position of the array, we need to check:

* If nums[i] > 0:
  * If prodMax > 0, it means we can add current position (nums[i]) to subarray[...i-1] for a bigger prodMax; else we reset prodMax (create a new subarray which starts from current position). The code is: ```prodMax = prodMax > 0 ? prodMax * nums[i] : nums[i] ```
  * If prodMin < 0, it means we can add current position (nums[i]) to subarray[...i-1] for a smaller prodMin; else we reset prodMin (create a new subarray which starts from current position). The code is: ```prodMin = prodMin < 0 ? prodMin * nums[i] : nums[i] ```

* If nums[i] < 0:
  * If prodMin < 0, it means we can add current position (nums[i]) to subarray[...i-1] for a bigger prodMax by multiplying nums[i] and prodMin (**since they are both negative, the multiplication will result in a big positive number**). Else we reset prodMax (create a new subarray which starts from current position). The code is: ```prodMax = prodMin < 0 ? prodMin * nums[i] : nums[i] ``` 
  * If prodMax > 0, it means we can add current position (nums[i]) to subarray[...i-1] for a smaller prodMin by multiplying nums[i] and prodMin (**since nums[i] < 0 and prodMax > 0, the multiplication will result in a big negative number**). Else we reset prodMin (create a new subarray which starts from current position). The code is: ```prodMin = prodMax > 0 ? prodMax * nums[i] : nums[i]```

Note that if nums[i] == 0, either logic works; so we don't need to care about the case. The same is for prodMax/prodMin == 0.

(An important logic is: if nums[i] < 0, new prodMax is decided by only `prodMin` and `nums[i]`, and **not** related to old prodMax. Since prodMax is always bigger than proMin, the multiplications with a negative value should always get a smaller value from prodMax and a bigger value from proMin. The logic is the same for new prodMin.)

For an implementation, we need to use posVal and negVal to save the results in advance, otherwise the modified prodMax/prodMin will impact the successive calculation. The code is:

```
class Solution {
    public int maxProduct(int[] nums) {
        int max = Integer.MIN_VALUE, prodMax = 1, prodMin = 1;
        for(int i = 0;i < nums.length;i++) {
            int posVal = prodMax * nums[i], negVal = prodMin * nums[i];
            if(nums[i] > 0) {
                prodMax = posVal > 0 ? posVal : nums[i];
                prodMin = negVal < 0 ? negVal : nums[i];
            } else {
                prodMax = negVal > 0 ? negVal : nums[i];
                prodMin = posVal < 0 ? posVal : nums[i];
            }
            max = Math.max(max, prodMax);
        }
        return max;
    }
}
```

A simplification is, we don't need to check posVal/negVal actually; we can simply get the max/min value. The code is:

```
class Solution {
    public int maxProduct(int[] nums) {
        int max = Integer.MIN_VALUE, prodMax = 1, prodMin = 1;
        for(int i = 0;i < nums.length;i++) {
            int posVal = prodMax * nums[i], negVal = prodMin * nums[i];
            if(nums[i] > 0) {
                prodMax = Math.max(posVal, nums[i]);
                prodMin = Math.min(negVal, nums[i]);
            } else {
                prodMax = Math.max(negVal, nums[i]);
                prodMin = Math.min(posVal, nums[i]);
            }
            max = Math.max(max, prodMax);
        }
        return max;
    }
}
```

The next step is, we can simply get the biggest/smallest value of (posVal, negVal, nums[i]) and avoid the check of nums[i]:


